ASP.NET Core MVC is a cross-platform, open-source framework for building modern, cloud-ready, and scalable web applications. It follows the Model-View-Controller (MVC) design pattern, which separates concerns:

Model → Represents application data and business logic.

View → Handles UI and presentation.

Controller → Manages user requests, interacts with the model, and returns responses.

Key features:

Built on .NET Core, making it lightweight and modular.

Supports dependency injection out of the box.

Provides middleware pipeline for request handling.

Enables RESTful APIs and Razor Pages.

Strong focus on security, performance, and testability.

📝 20 ASP.NET Core MVC Interview Q&A (Company-Level)
Basics
Q: What is ASP.NET Core MVC?
A: A framework for building web apps using the MVC pattern, running cross-platform on .NET Core.

Q: Difference between ASP.NET MVC and ASP.NET Core MVC?
A: Core MVC is cross-platform, modular, faster, and supports dependency injection natively.

Q: What is Middleware in ASP.NET Core?
A: Components in the request pipeline that handle requests/responses (e.g., authentication, logging).

Q: Explain the MVC pattern.
A: Model (data), View (UI), Controller (logic) → separation of concerns.

Controllers & Routing
Q: How does routing work in ASP.NET Core MVC?
A: Uses endpoint routing defined in Program.cs or Startup.cs with MapControllerRoute.

Q: What are Action Methods?
A: Public methods in controllers that handle incoming requests and return responses.

Q: Difference between IActionResult and ActionResult<T>?
A: IActionResult is non-generic, while ActionResult<T> provides type safety for responses.

Models & Data
Q: What is Entity Framework Core?
A: ORM for database access, supporting LINQ queries and migrations.

Q: How do you implement validation in MVC Core?
A: Using Data Annotations ([Required], [StringLength]) or Fluent Validation.

Q: What is ViewModel?
A: A class that shapes data specifically for the view, separate from domain models.

Views & Razor
Q: What is Razor?
A: A templating engine that combines C# with HTML for dynamic views.

Q: Difference between Partial View and Layout?
A: Layout defines a common structure (like master page), Partial View is reusable UI snippet.

Q: What are Tag Helpers?
A: Server-side components that generate HTML dynamically (e.g., <form asp-action="Login">).

Dependency Injection & Services
Q: How is Dependency Injection implemented in ASP.NET Core?
A: Using built-in DI container with AddScoped, AddTransient, AddSingleton.

Q: Difference between Scoped, Transient, and Singleton?
A:

Scoped → per request

Transient → new instance every time

Singleton → single instance for app lifetime

Security & Authentication
Q: How do you implement Authentication in ASP.NET Core?
A: Using Identity, JWT tokens, or external providers (Google, Facebook).

Q: What is CSRF protection in MVC Core?
A: Anti-forgery tokens (@Html.AntiForgeryToken()) prevent cross-site request forgery.

Advanced Topics
Q: What is Middleware vs Filters?
A: Middleware works at pipeline level, Filters work at MVC action level (e.g., AuthorizeFilter).

Q: How do you implement Logging in ASP.NET Core?
A: Using built-in ILogger<T> with providers like Console, Debug, or Serilog.

Q: How do you improve performance in ASP.NET Core MVC apps?
A: Caching, async programming, minimizing middleware, using CDN, and optimizing EF Core queries.
